commentBody:
@Steve L
you're almost 100% right. I've known bad dogs with good owners, but they were rescues and certainly their earlier owners or life experiences are to blame. 

I remember reading a fascinating article about how wolves became dogs, and the gist was "did we train them, or did they train us?"  There's a good argument for the latter.

@Steve L

Bet your comment here will be top of the reader picks! Totally agree! It's one of a handful of words I never like seeing in here. Wish there were a better way to clue it.  Poor pups! 

I just bought my grandpup a new toy. Can't wait to give it to her!

@Vaer

Cute. But here are some real-life non-canine clues, courtesy of xwordinfo.com:

[Scoundrel] (7 occurrences); [Blackguard] (5); [Despicable sort] (2);  [Skunk]; [Contemptible sort]; [Base man]; [Meanie];  [Rotter] and [Heel] (1 each).

@Vaer

I definitely thought of you today with BEL.  ☺️  

AND I LIKE YOUR SUGGESTION!

@Steve L

The clue is actually questionable. Webster's Dictionary says a CUR is "a mongrel or inferior dog," not "no good." 

I'll leave the checking of a dozen dictionaries to defend it to you guys.

@SBK in TO

We refer to our adult children’s animals as our granddogs and grandcats. Not any progeny of our own animals. (Because we travel a lot, we don’t have pets of our own). I suspect that may be what Heathie was referring to. 

In that context, it makes sense when you haven’t been blessed with actual grandchildren yet.

@Bob T.

I had no idea what the English term was so I had to rely on crosses, but the Polish "fastrygować" is a term I've known since childhood. All kids were taught to sew in Polish elementary school in the 1980s and 1990s. I was quite bad at it and only ever "mastered" fastrygowanie 🤣

Strangely enough, the Polish word comes from the German "fast riggen", meaning "to tie together strongly" - even though there specifically is nothing strong about fastryga...

@SBK in TO

I guess my post somehow wasn't clear enough for you. Let me amend one sentence:

I had no idea what the English term *for sewing loosely* was so I had to rely on crosses *to get BASTE, but its Polish equivalent of* "fastrygować" is a term I've known since childhood.

@SBK in TO
Just so you know:  we can machine-BASTE, too.  I very seldom do any sewn basting when constructing a quilt; I pin-baste (but I just call it 'pinning') and I use a particular foot and stitch-length.  
(I no longer make clothes; if I did, I'd probably BASTE...)

@Weak

